CreditCard Users Churn Prediction

Background:

The Thera bank recently saw a steep decline in the number of users of their credit card, credit cards are a good source of income for banks because of different kinds of fees charged by the banks like annual fees, balance transfer fees, and cash advance fees, late payment fees, foreign transaction fees, and others. Some fees are charged on every user irrespective of usage, while others are charged under specified circumstances.

Customers leaving credit cards services would lead bank to loss, so the bank wants to analyze the data of customers and identify the customers who will leave their credit card services and reason for same so that bank could improve upon those areas

You as a Data scientist at Thera bank need to come up with a classification model that will help bank improve their services so that customers do not renounce their credit cards

Objective:

Explore and visualize the dataset. Build a classification model to predict if the customer is going to churn or not Optimize the model using appropriate techniques Generate a set of insights and recommendations that will help the bank Data Dictionary:

  • CLIENTNUM: Client number. Unique identifier for the customer holding the account
  • Attrition_Flag: Internal event (customer activity) variable - if the account is closed then 1 else 0
  • Customer_Age: Age in Years
  • Gender: Gender of the account holder
  • Dependent_count: Number of dependents
  • Education_Level: Educational Qualification of the account holder
  • Marital_Status: Marital Status of the account holder
  • Income_Category: Annual Income Category of the account holder
  • Card_Category: Type of Card
  • Months_on_book: Period of relationship with the bank
  • Total_Relationship_Count: Total no. of products held by the customer
  • Months_Inactive_12_mon: No. of months inactive in the last 12 months
  • Contacts_Count_12_mon: No. of Contacts in the last 12 months
  • Credit_Limit: Credit Limit on the Credit Card
  • Total_Revolving_Bal: Total Revolving Balance on the Credit Card
  • Avg_Open_To_Buy: Open to Buy Credit Line (Average of last 12 months)
  • Total_Amt_Chng_Q4_Q1: Change in Transaction Amount (Q4 over Q1)
  • Total_Trans_Amt: Total Transaction Amount (Last 12 months)
  • Total_Trans_Ct: Total Transaction Count (Last 12 months)
  • Total_Ct_Chng_Q4_Q1: Change in Transaction Count (Q4 over Q1)
  • Avg_Utilization_Ratio: Average Card Utilization Ratio

# Checking categorical data (insights provided after gragh)

f = plt.figure(figsize=(16, 30))
gs = f.add_gridspec(5, 2)
i,j=0,0
for col_names in object_columns:
    ax = f.add_subplot(gs[i, j])    
    ax.text(.5,.9,col_names,horizontalalignment='center',transform=ax.transAxes, family = 'serif',size = 'large')
    if col_names == 'Income_Category':
        ax1 = sns.countplot (data = df, x= col_names,palette = 'cool',order=['Less than $40K','$40K - $60K','$80K - $120K','$60K - $80K','$120K +','Unknown'])
    else:
        ax1 = sns.countplot (data = df, x= col_names,palette = 'cool') 
    total = len(df[col_names]) # length of the column
    for p in ax1.patches:
        percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total) # percentage of each class of the category
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.1 # width of the plot
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()           # hieght of the plot
        ax1.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size = 11) # annotate the percantage             
    ax.yaxis.label.set_size(15)
    if j==1:
        i+=1
        j=0
    else: j+=1
        
plt.show()
f.tight_layout()

Insights:¶

  • This is an imbalanced dataset, only 16% of customers have churned
  • 30% of the customers are graduates, followed by 19.9% customers from high school
  • 35% of the customers earn less than 40k
  • 93% of the customers have card as 'Blue', so the dependant varuable will be highly influenced by 'blue' categrory
  • Most of the customers apprximateetly 53% have 2 to 3 dependants
  • 23% customer hold 3 products each as per relationhip_count. 79% of the cusmers hold over 3 or more products
  • 38% of the customers have been inactive in the past 38 months
  • 64% of the customers have been contacted 2-3 times in past 12 mnonths
In [209]:
# While doing uni-variate analysis of numerical variables we want to study their central tendency 
# and dispersion.
# Let us write a function that will help us create boxplot and histogram for any input numerical 
# variable.
# This function takes the numerical column as the input and returns the boxplots 
# and histograms for the variable.
# Let us see if this help us write faster and cleaner code.
def histogram_boxplot(feature, figsize=(15,10), bins = None):
    """ Boxplot and histogram combined
    feature: 1-d feature array
    figsize: size of fig (default (9,8))
    bins: number of bins (default None / auto)
    """
    label="Skewness: %.2f"%(feature.skew())    
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(nrows = 2, # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
                                           sharex = True, # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
                                           gridspec_kw = {"height_ratios": (.25, .75)}, 
                                           figsize = figsize 
                                           ) # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color='violet') # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.distplot(feature, kde=F, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins,color = 'orange',label = label) if bins else sns.distplot(feature, kde=False, ax=ax_hist2,color='tab:cyan',label = label) # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(np.mean(feature), color='purple', linestyle='--') # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(np.median(feature), color='black', linestyle='-') # Add median to the histogram
    plt.legend(fontsize = 'x-large')
    plt.show()

# this function will plot a continous variable against Target variable
def analyze_continous_var(col):
    palette = 'Accent'
    f = plt.figure(figsize=(16, 6))
    gs = f.add_gridspec(1, 3)
    ax = f.add_subplot(gs[0, 0])  
    plot1 = sns.boxplot(y=col,x='Attrition_Flag',data=df,palette = palette, linewidth= 0.5)
    #ax = f.add_subplot(gs[1, 0])
    #sns.violinplot(y='age',x='Target',data=df,palette = 'Accent')
    ax = f.add_subplot(gs[0, 1])
    plot2 = sns.stripplot(y=col,x='Attrition_Flag',data=df,palette = palette, jitter=0.30, linewidth= 0.1, edgecolor ='blue')
    ax = f.add_subplot(gs[0, 2])
    plot2 = sns.violinplot(y=col,x='Attrition_Flag',data=df,palette = palette, linewidth= 0.5)    
    plt.show()

Checking Categorical data individually w.r.t Target variable¶

The function created below will create a graph - The graph will display all categories and for each category it will simply display % of Customers for category

In [233]:
def display_categorical_data(col):
    f= plt.figure(figsize=(14,6))
    todal_n= []
    i=0    
    ax_plot2 = sns.countplot (data = df, x= col,hue= 'Attrition_Flag',palette = 'plasma_r')
    ax_plot2.text(.1,.7,'Percentage of Customers left the bank',horizontalalignment='center',verticalalignment='top',transform=ax.transAxes, family = 'serif',size = 'large')
    cnt = df[col].nunique()
    for p in ax_plot2.patches:               
        todal_n.append(p.get_height())
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.1 # width of the plot
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()           # hieght of the plot
        if i>= cnt:        
            per = '{:.1f}%'.format(todal_n[i]*100/todal_n[i-cnt])
            ax_plot2.annotate(per, (x, y), size = 11) # annotate the percantage   
        i+=1
    ax_plot2.yaxis.label.set_size(15)
    ax_plot2.xaxis.label.set_size(12)   
    if col == 'job':
        plt.xticks(rotation=30)
    
    plt.show()

#print unique values and counts for all Categorical columns; we will convert these columns and compare these counts later
object_columns = list(df.describe(include=['object']).T.index)
total_rows = len(df)
for col in object_columns:    
    print(f'Unique values count and % for column "{col}" are:\n')
    vc = pd.DataFrame(df[col].value_counts())
    vc['per'] = round(vc[col]/total_rows*100) 
    vc.columns = ['Count','Percentage of Overall Data']    
    print(tabulate(vc, headers = 'keys', tablefmt = 'fancy_grid'))

Building the model

In [355]:
##  Function to calculate different metric scores of the model - Accuracy, Recall and Precision
def get_metrics_score(model,train,test,train_y,test_y,flag=True):
    '''
    model : classifier to predict values of X

    '''
    # defining an empty list to store train and test results
    score_list=[] 
    
    pred_train = model.predict(train)
    pred_test = model.predict(test)
    
    train_acc = model.score(train,train_y)
    test_acc = model.score(test,test_y)
    
    train_recall = metrics.recall_score(train_y,pred_train)
    test_recall = metrics.recall_score(test_y,pred_test)
    
    train_precision = metrics.precision_score(train_y,pred_train)
    test_precision = metrics.precision_score(test_y,pred_test)
    
    score_list.extend((train_acc,test_acc,train_recall,test_recall,train_precision,test_precision))
        
    # If the flag is set to True then only the following print statements will be dispayed. The default value is set to True.
    if flag == True: 
        print("Accuracy on training set : ",model.score(train,train_y))
        print("Accuracy on test set : ",model.score(test,test_y))
        print("Recall on training set : ",metrics.recall_score(train_y,pred_train))
        print("Recall on test set : ",metrics.recall_score(test_y,pred_test))
        print("Precision on training set : ",metrics.precision_score(train_y,pred_train))
        print("Precision on test set : ",metrics.precision_score(test_y,pred_test))
    
    return score_list
In [263]:
def make_confusion_matrix(model,y_actual,labels=[1, 0]):
    '''
    model : classifier to predict values of X
    y_actual : ground truth  
    
    '''
    y_predict = model.predict(X_test)
    cm=metrics.confusion_matrix( y_actual, y_predict, labels=[0, 1])
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = [i for i in ["Actual - No","Actual - Yes"]],
                  columns = [i for i in ['Predicted - No','Predicted - Yes']])
    group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}".format(value) for value in
                cm.flatten()]
    group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in
                         cm.flatten()/np.sum(cm)]
    labels = [f"{v1}\n{v2}" for v1, v2 in
              zip(group_counts,group_percentages)]
    labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2,2)
    plt.figure(figsize = (10,7))
    sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=labels,fmt='')
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')

# Choose the type of classifier. 
lr_estimator = LogisticRegression(random_state=1,solver='saga')

# Grid of parameters to choose from
parameters = {'C': np.arange(0.1,1.1,0.1)}

# Run the grid search
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(lr_estimator, parameters, scoring='recall')
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(X_train_over, y_train_over)

# Set the clf to the best combination of parameters
lr_estimator = grid_obj.best_estimator_

# Fit the best algorithm to the data. 
lr_estimator.fit(X_train_over, y_train_over)

PIPELINES

Model building - Bagging and Boosting

  • Tune all the models using grid search - Use pipelines in hyperparameter tuning
  • use grid search and random search for hyperparameter tuning

models = []  # Empty list to store all the models

    (
        "LR",
        Pipeline(
            steps=[
                ("scaler", StandardScaler()),
                ("log_reg", LogisticRegression(random_state=1)),
            ]
        ),
    )
)

    )
)

In [289]:
results = []  # Empty list to store all model's CV scores
names = []  # Empty list to store name of the models

# loop through all models to get the mean cross validated score
for name, model in models:
    scoring = "recall"
    kfold = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=1)  
    cv_result = cross_val_score(estimator=model, X=X_train, y=y_train, scoring=scoring, cv=kfold)
    results.append(cv_result)
    names.append(name)
    print(f"{name}: {cv_result.mean() * 100}")

Hyperparameter Tuning

We will use pipelines with StandardScaler and XGBOOST model and tune the model using GridSearchCV and RandomizedSearchCV. We will also compare the performance and time taken by these two methods - grid search and randomized search.

XGBOOST with GridSearchCV

In [329]:
%%time 

# Creating pipeline
pipe = make_pipeline(StandardScaler(), XGBClassifier(random_state=1))

# Parameter grid to pass in GridSearchCV
parameters = {'xgbclassifier__n_estimators': [75,100,125,150], 
              'xgbclassifier__subsample':[0.7, 0.8, 0.9, 1],
              'xgbclassifier__gamma':[0, 1, 3, 5],
              'xgbclassifier__colsample_bytree':[0.7, 0.8, 0.9, 1]
              }

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.recall_score)

# Calling GridSearchCV
grid_cv = GridSearchCV(estimator=pipe, param_grid=parameters, scoring=scorer, cv=5)

# Fitting parameters in GridSeachCV
grid_cv.fit(X_train, y_train)

print("Best Parameters:{} \nScore: {}".format(grid_cv.best_params_, grid_cv.best_score_))

This is the best model so far- XGboost with GridSearchCV¶

XGBOOST with RandomizedSearchCV

In [335]:
%%time 

# Creating pipeline
pipe = make_pipeline(StandardScaler(), XGBClassifier(random_state=1))

# Parameter grid to pass in GridSearchCV
parameters = {'xgbclassifier__n_estimators': [75,100,125,150], 
              'xgbclassifier__subsample':[0.7, 0.8, 0.9, 1],
              'xgbclassifier__gamma':[0, 1, 3, 5],
              'xgbclassifier__colsample_bytree':[0.7, 0.8, 0.9, 1]
              }

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.recall_score)

# Calling GridSearchCV
randomized_cv = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=pipe, param_distributions=parameters,n_iter=50, scoring=scorer, cv=5, random_state=7)

# Fitting parameters in GridSeachCV
randomized_cv.fit(X_train, y_train)

print("Best Parameters:{} \nScore: {}".format(randomized_cv.best_params_, randomized_cv.best_score_))

AdaBoost with GridSearchCV

In [343]:
%%time 

# Creating pipeline
pipe = make_pipeline(StandardScaler(), AdaBoostClassifier(random_state=1))

# Parameter grid to pass in GridSearchCV
param_grid = {
    "adaboostclassifier__n_estimators": np.arange(10, 110, 10),
    "adaboostclassifier__learning_rate": [0.1, 0.01, 0.2, 0.05, 1],
    "adaboostclassifier__base_estimator": [
        DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=2, random_state=1),
        DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=3, random_state=1),
    ],
}

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.recall_score)

# Calling GridSearchCV
grid_cv = GridSearchCV(estimator=pipe, param_grid=param_grid, scoring=scorer, cv=5)

# Fitting parameters in GridSeachCV
grid_cv.fit(X_train, y_train)

print(
    "Best Parameters:{} \nScore: {}".format(grid_cv.best_params_, grid_cv.best_score_)
)

Best Parameters:{'adaboostclassifier__base_estimator': DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=2, random_state=1), 'adaboostclassifier__learning_rate': 1, 'adaboostclassifier__n_estimators': 50} 
Score: 0.8893809413401345
Wall time: 4min 34s

AdaBoost with RandomizedSearchCV

In [347]:
%%time

# Creating pipeline
pipe = make_pipeline(StandardScaler(), AdaBoostClassifier(random_state=1))

# Parameter grid to pass in GridSearchCV
param_grid = {
    "adaboostclassifier__n_estimators": np.arange(10, 110, 10),
    "adaboostclassifier__learning_rate": [0.1, 0.01, 0.2, 0.05, 1],
    "adaboostclassifier__base_estimator": [
        DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=2, random_state=1),
        DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=3, random_state=1),
    ],
}
# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.recall_score)

#Calling RandomizedSearchCV
abc_tuned2 = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=pipe, param_distributions=param_grid, n_iter=50, scoring=scorer, cv=5, random_state=1)

#Fitting parameters in RandomizedSearchCV
abc_tuned2.fit(X_train,y_train)

print("Best parameters are {} with CV score={}:" .format(abc_tuned2.best_params_,abc_tuned2.best_score_))

Best parameters are {'adaboostclassifier__n_estimators': 50, 'adaboostclassifier__learning_rate': 1, 'adaboostclassifier__base_estimator': DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=2, random_state=1)} with CV score=0.8893809413401345:
Wall time: 2min 22s

The RandomizedSearchCV completed in 2 minute 22 seconds

Feature importance

In [364]:
def feat_importance(model, X_Train):
    fi = pd.DataFrame()
    fi['Col'] = X_train.columns
    fi['imp'] = np.round(abs(model[1].feature_importances_),4)
    fi = fi.sort_values(by='imp')
    plt.figure(figsize=(16,14))
    plt.barh(fi['Col'], fi['imp'], color='violet', align='center')
    plt.title('FEATURE IMPORTANCE')
    plt.show()
In [365]:
feat_importance(xgb_classifier_tuned1, X_train)

Insights:

  • Total_Trans_Ct: This is strong feature, customers with more transactiosn are less likely to leave
  • Total_Relationship_Count: this feature is seond most important to the model, customer with more products and extrenely less are less likely to leave
  • Total_Trans_Amt: customers with more amoount are less likely to leave

Comparing all models

In [356]:
# defining list of models
models = [xgb_classifier_tuned1, xgb_classifier_tuned2,ada_classifier_tuned1,ada_classifier_tuned2]

# defining empty lists to add train and test results
acc_train = []
acc_test = []
recall_train = []
recall_test = []
precision_train = []
precision_test = []

# looping through all the models to get the metrics score - Accuracy, Recall and Precision
for model in models:

    #print(model)
    j = get_metrics_score(model,X_train,X_test,y_train,y_test, False)
    #print(j)
    acc_train.append(j[0])
    acc_test.append(j[1])
    recall_train.append(j[2])
    recall_test.append(j[3])
    precision_train.append(j[4])
    precision_test.append(j[5])
In [357]:
comparison_frame = pd.DataFrame(
    {
        "Model": [
            "XGBoost with GridSearchCV",
            "XGBoost with RandomizedSearchCV",
            "AdaBoost with GridSearchCV",
            "AdaBoost with RandomizedSearchCV"       
        ],
        "Train_Accuracy": acc_train,
        "Test_Accuracy": acc_test,
        "Train_Recall": recall_train,
        "Test_Recall": recall_test,
        "Train_Precision": precision_train,
        "Test_Precision": precision_test,
    }
)

# Sorting models in decreasing order of test recall
comparison_frame.sort_values(by="Test_Recall", ascending=False)

Insights¶

  • GridSearchCV has better results than Randomized searchCV for Adaboost and XGboost.
  • the results are maginnaly better in grid searcv, but time taken is substantially higher, so this is a tradeoff.
  • The best and the slowest model is XGBoost with GridSearchCV
  • The quickest model is XGBoost with RandomizedSearchCV ; also it has the secnd best results, so this is a winner.
